\subsection{Information-Conserving Arithmetic and the Dual-Zero Axiom}
\label{sec:dualzero-axiom}

\subsubsection{Motivation: The Lie of Zero in Arithmetic}

In standard real arithmetic the symbol $0$ is conventionally understood to represent ``nothing.'' This interpretation is fundamentally incorrect when describing physical reality. Consider the elementary division
\[
10 \div 3 = 3.\overline{3}.
\]
Multiplying back,
\[
3 \times 3 = 9.\overline{9},
\]
which differs from the original $10$ by an infinitesimal remainder. In every arithmetic ``transaction'' (multiplication, division, addition, or subtraction) an infinitesimal loss or gain occurs. When these operations are repeated trillions of times — precisely the situation encountered on a non-compact infinite manifold with a continuous or densely discrete spectrum — the accumulated zeros erase an unbounded quantity of information.

Physics, as an exact description of Nature, cannot tolerate any irreversible loss of information. The symbol $0$ therefore actually denotes ``anything less than one whole unit.'' On the infinite right conoid of the SAM3 framework, the Dirac operator produces an infinite tower of modes. Treating the high-mode tail with ordinary real arithmetic would discard information at every scale, violating unitarity, hermiticity, and the variational principle that enforces the Riemann hypothesis.

To resolve this, we introduce the **Dual-Zero hyperreal algebra** \( \mathbb{R}_{[0,-0]} \).

\subsubsection{Definition of the Dual-Zero Algebra}

The algebra consists of elements of the truncated form
\[
a + \epsilon b + \epsilon^2 c, \qquad a,b,c \in \mathbb{R},
\]
where the infinitesimal generator is realized by the sequence
\begin{equation}
\epsilon(n) = \omega_0 (-1)^n n^{-n}, \qquad \omega_0 > 0,
\label{eq:epsilon-def}
\end{equation}
and \( n \) indexes the eigenvalues/modes of the regularized Dirac operator on the conoid. Multiplication is performed with truncation at order \( \epsilon^2 \):
\[
(a + \epsilon b + \epsilon^2 c)(d + \epsilon e + \epsilon^2 f) = ad + \epsilon(ae + bd) + \epsilon^2(af + be + cd).
\]
The symmetric regularization map
\[
\operatorname{Reg}_2(f)(\lambda) = \lim_{\delta \to 0^+} \frac{f(\lambda + \delta) + f(\lambda - \delta)}{2}
\]
is applied to operators whose spectrum lies away from zero.

This construction ensures that **no remainder is ever set exactly to zero**. Every infinitesimal loss or gain is explicitly tracked and conserved.

\subsubsection{Why This Exact Form? Derivation from Information Conservation}

The specific choice \eqref{eq:epsilon-def} is not ad hoc. It is the unique (up to the free scale \( \omega_0 \)) infinitesimal that satisfies all physical and geometric requirements of the SAM3 model simultaneously:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Exact information conservation.} The oscillation \( (-1)^n \) encodes the duality of gain and loss inherent in repeating decimals. It guarantees that positive and negative infinitesimals appear symmetrically, so that \( \operatorname{Reg}_2 \) never collapses any remainder to the classical zero.
    
    \item \textbf{Super-exponential decoupling.} The decay \( n^{-n} = \exp(-n \ln n) \) is faster than any exponential. This ensures that corrections to low-lying eigenvalues (which determine fermion masses, Yukawa couplings, and the Higgs vacuum) remain negligible (\( |\delta\lambda_k| \le 2\omega_0 \exp(-k \ln k) \)), while the infinite high-mode tail is still fully accounted for. Slower decay would contaminate observable physics; faster decay or truncation would re-introduce exact zeros.
    
    \item \textbf{Compatibility with conoid geometry and symmetry.} The period-2 oscillation \( (-1)^n \) commutes with the \( \sin(2v) \) periodicity of the right conoid metric and with the $12$-bridge icosahedral ($2I$) projectors. This preserves hermiticity of the full Dirac operator \( D = D_\infty \otimes 1 + 1 \otimes D_F \) and the first-order condition of the spectral triple.
    
    \item \textbf{Consistency with the variational information principle.} The information current \( J(k_1,k_2) \) and the action \( S_I = \int |J|^2\,d\mu \) remain real and stationary precisely on the Riemann critical line \( \operatorname{Re}(s)=1/2 \) only when the Dual-Zero regulator is used. Any other regulator shifts the variational minimum off the line or destroys zero-mode normalizability (\( \psi_+(u) \sim u^{-1/2} \)).
\end{enumerate}

